#Text=Isop is reasonable long lasting: young roots are good set, slips better.
#Text=A good pot-hearbe.
#Text=Iuly-flowers, commonly called Gilly-flowers, or Cloue-Iuly-flowers (I call them so, because they flowre in Iuly) they haue the name of Cloues, of their sent.
#Text=I may well call them the King of flowers (except the Rose) and the best sort of them are called Queene-Iuly flowers.

#Text=I haue of them nine or ten seuerall colours, and diuers of them as big as Roses: of all flowers (saue the Damaske Rose) they are the most pleasant to sight and smell: they last not past three or foure yeeres vnremoued.
#Text=Take the sl•ps (without shanks) aud set any time, saue in extreme frost, but especially at Michael tide.
#Text=Their vse is much in ornament, and conforting the spirits, by the sence of smelling.
#Text=Iuly flowers of the wall, or wall-Iuly-flowers wall-flowers, or Bee-flowers, or Winter-Iuly-flowers, because
#Text=
#Text=
#Text=growing in the walles, euen in Winter, and good for Bees, will grow euen in stone walls, they will seeme dead in Summer, and yet reuiue in Winter.

#Text=They yeeld seed plentifully, which you may sow at any time, or in any broken earth, especially on the top of a mud-wall, but moist, you may set the root before it be brancht, euery slip that is not flowr ' d will take root, or crop him in Summer, and he will flower in Winter: but his Winter-seed is vntimely.
#Text=This and Palmes are exceeding good, and timely for Bees.
#Text=Leekes yeeld seed the second yeere, vnremoued and die, vnlesse you remoue them, vsuall to eate with salt and bread, as Onyons alwaies greene, good pot-hearb, euill for the eyes.
#Text=Lauendar Spike would be remoued within 7 yeeres, or eight at the most.
#Text=Slips twined as Isop and Sage, would take best at Michael-tide.
#Text=This flower is good for Bees, most comfortable for smelling, except Roses: and kept dry, is as strong after a yeere, and when it is gathered.
#Text=The water of this is comfortable.
#Text=White Lauendar would be remoued sooner.
#Text=Lettice yeelds seed the first yeere, and dyes: sow betime, and if you would haue them Cabbage for Sallets, remoue them as you doe Cabbage.
#Text=They are vsuall in Sallets, and the pot.

#Text=Lillies white and red, remoued once in three or foure yeeres their roots yeeld many Sets, like the Garlicke, Michael-tide is the best: they grow high, after they get roote: these roots are good to breake a Byle, as are Mallowes and Sorrell.
